df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.54ce51ca-25a8-4857-b36e-51fba5d9b3ed.description=Produces a summary report of the steps executed up to (but not including) itself. Input Parameters\: runHistoryID - the numerical id for the run history in the database. If blank, the id of the current run history is used. formatHTMLYesNo - if true, formats operation result as an HTML table. Default is plain text. flowVariableName - if defined, places a bidimensional array[N][4] in a flow variable with this name. N is the number of steps in the report. The four columns contain\: at index[0] the path to the step in the flow, index [1] has the step name, index[2] the response and index[3] the description. Responses\: success - The command executed successfully. failure - The command failed to execute. Results\: SummaryReport - The summary report, formatted as HTML or plain text. If a flow variable name has been specified, it will contain the array of steps. FailureMessage - The failure message, in case the operation failed. Note\: The following JavaScript code shows how to access the array of steps from within a scriptlet\: var reportArray \= scriptletContext.get("my_report_flow_variable_name") if (reportArray) { var os \= java.lang.System.out; for (i \= 0; i < reportArray.length; i++) { var stepArray \= reportArray[i]; for (j \= 0; j < stepArray.length; j++) { os.println("reportArray[" + i + "][" + j + "] \= " + stepArray[j]); } } } df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.55b5ecee-2dfb-41b1-a033-85b3feee26e7.prompt=Enter password df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.746a89ca-0921-4387-9233-ed3633046cf5.prompt=Enter username df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.81e23a65-5a50-4b0d-ab5e-61c2538a086b.description=Releases a lock with an id given by the value of the lockId input. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.

Responses\:
   success - the only response returned.

Results\:
   there are no results.

Notes\:
1) The operation only releases locks acquired by the current run. 
   It cannot release another run's locks.

2) The operation succeeds whether or not there is a lock held 
   by the current run with the supplied id.
df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.8c427b44-266d-4954-9da4-4e98c19a2c14.description=
Allows a user to select how they should be notified of the outcome of a flow, and shows them a message in that way.

Inputs\:
notifyData -  The text of the notification message.
notifyMethod - The method of notification (Write to File, Email, Display or None). This value is case-insensitive.
subject - A description of what the notification is about. 
destination - The destination of the notification (email address or filename). This field is required when notifyMethod is Email or Write to File.
notificationServer - The email server to send the notification through. This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
from - The originator of the message (email "from" address).This field is required when notifyMethod is Email.
serverPort - The port the service to notify on the server is running on. This field used when notifyMethod is Email, and it is optional (it defaults to 25 if not specified).
htmlEmail - Default value is true. The value should be true if the email is in rich text/html format. The value should be false to send the email in plain text format.

Responses\:
success - The user was notified.
failure - Notification failed.

As mentioned above, some inputs are required for certain types of notification methods. In order to schedule a flow that in turn uses this flow, all of the required fields for the given notification method must be supplied, or else the flow will not be able to execute to completion. For example, if "notifyMethod" is "File", then the "destination" input must also be specified.
df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.9c57379c-1fe0-423e-9ee8-ee5e5e9dcf8c.description=
Adds a flow variable into the local context (available to itself and child flows only)

Input Parameters\:
keyName - the name of the flow variable to use
myValue - the value to assign the flow variable

Responses\:
success - assigned the flow variable

Scriptlet Example\:
[$scriptletContext putGlobal\: $keyName, $myValue];

df7c7781-7ab0-444d-b9ab-50e397275d66.de4765f5-ec37-45e5-9495-d1c668c818c2.description=
Iterates through a list of values. If the list changes while running, the updates will be appended to the list.

Inputs\:
separator - The list separator (or delimiter).
list - The list to be split

Responses\:
has more - Another value was in the list, and has been returned.
failure - failed to process the list.
no more - The iterator has gone fully through the list. This response will only be returned once per iteration through the list, a subsequent call to the Iterator will restart the Iteration through the list.

Returns\:
The current element of the list, if the response is has more
